shoot:description:Aside from a few iPhone shots up at elevation, the photos here are from back down at/around home, where Northern Flickers were feeding nestlings, Rufous Hummingbirds came by the feeder, and dragonflies were plentiful down at the ponds.
shoot:favorite:2026-06-23-082539-41-R5PT9035-sm.jpg
2026-06-16-113608-549-IMG_3167-sm.jpg:description:I saw this pair up in the sky in the middle of the day, and I was initially unsure of what I was looking at.  Their long wings and deep flapping motion looked like terns!
2026-06-23-082433-59-R5PT9003-sm.jpg:description:I was facing the cavity opening head-on, so it was really lucky that the male stopped on the perch off to the side to allow this shot to be taken!
2026-06-23-130345-19-R5PT9106-sm.jpg:description:I missed the focus on this shot.  Dang.
2026-06-23-130427-05-R5PT9173-sm.jpg:description:I'm keeping a few of these shots that show the tail feathers, because that's one way to distinguish Rufous from Allen's Hummingbirds.  After looking at some example photos however I'm not sure anything can really be determined from these photos.
2026-06-25-090156-71-R5PT9204-sm.jpg:description:This series of shots worked OK despite shooting through the kitchen window.
